This paper is primarily focused on evaluating the effectiveness of differentially private machine learning in practice, with a particular emphasis on the trade-offs between privacy and utility. As such, it is likely to be relevant to several different sub-categories of computer science. 

The most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security), as the paper is primarily concerned with evaluating the privacy guarantees provided by differentially private machine learning mechanisms. 

The second most likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), as the paper is also concerned with evaluating the utility of differentially private machine learning mechanisms, and includes experiments with logistic regression and neural network models. 

The third most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), as the paper discusses the use of iterative learning procedures in differentially private machine learning, which may involve the use of specialized data structures and algorithms. 

The fourth most likely category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as the paper is concerned with the practical implementation of machine learning algorithms and the trade-offs between privacy and utility. 

The fifth most likely category is cs.CY (Computers and Society), as the paper also discusses the broader societal implications of differentially private machine learning and the need for careful consideration of privacy concerns in the development of machine learning systems.
